th="56" height="58" alt="For Teachers &amp; Students icon"></td>            <td width="90%"><img src="images/teachers-title.gif" width="290" height="17" alt="Programs for Teachers &amp; Students"></td>          </tr>        </table>                <table width="90%" border="0" cellspacing="10" cellpadding="0">          <tr>             <td width="38%"><a href="http://www.artsconnected.org"><img src="images/artsconnected-screen.jpg" width="232" height="128" border="0"></a></td>            <td width="62%" valign="top">               <p><b>ArtsConnectEd</b><br>                <a href="http://www.artsconnected.org">www.artsconnected.org</a><br>                <i>ArtsConnectEd</i> is the Institute's comprehensive educational                 resource, an online database of images, information, educational                 tours and materials. Using the power of the Internet to stimulate                 new approaches to learning, the goal of ArtsConnectEd is to make                 arts education timely, engaging, interactive, and pertinent for                 teachers, parents, students and the general public.</p>              </td>          </tr>        </table>        <table width="90%" border="0" cellspacing="10" cellpadding="0">          <tr>            <td colspan="2" height="77" bgcolor="#CCCCCC" valign="top">               <p><img src="images/featured-programs.gif" width="168" height="18" align="top" border="0" alt="Featured Programs"></p>              <blockquote>			  <a href="../get-more"><img src="images/get-more-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" align="left"  border="0" hspace="8" alt="Get More from Your Visit"></a><b>Get More from Your Visit</b><br>              <a href="../get-more">www.artsmia.org/get-more</a><br>              Get More From Your Visit offers a wealth of resources 			  to help you prepare for your visit to the Institute.</p>                <p><a href="../surrounded-by-beauty"><img src="images/sbb-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" align="left" border="0" hspace="8" alt="Surrounded by Beauty"></a><b>Surrounded by Beauty</b><br>              <a href="../surrounded-by-beauty">www.artsmia.org/surrounded-by-beauty</a><br>              Surrounded by Beauty is an online resource for K - 12 students and teachers 			  featuring Native American works of art from The Minneapolis Institute 			  of Arts' permanent collection.<br>                  <img src="images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="8" alt=" "></p>                </blockquote>            </td>            <td height="77">&nbsp;</td>          </tr>        </table>        <table width="90%" border="0" cellspacing="10" cellpadding="0">          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%" height="49">               <p><b><a href="../animals"><img src="images/amazing-animals-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Amazing Animals"></a></b></p>            </td>            <td width="93%" height="49"><b>Amazing Animals</b><br>              <a href="../animals">www.artsmia.org/animals</a> <br>              Eight works of art from around the world reveal the enduring human               fascination with animals. Accompanying text relates each work to               the &quot;Amazing Animals&quot; theme and provides background information               about the work of art and how it was made. Each entry includes discussion               questions for grades K - 6.</td>          </tr>          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../art_in_america"><img src="images/art-in-america-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Art in America"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>Art in America</b><br>              <a href="../art_in_america">www.artsmia.org/art_in_america</a> <br>              From a 12th-century Native American ceramic bowl to the work of               a contemporary New York artist, the art in this unit illustrates               the variety of American art in the Institute's collection. The accompanying               text includes background information and discussion questions. Other               resources include a framework of categories for comparing works               of art and a variety of classroom activities, with an illustrated               timeline and postcard images for use in the activities.</td>          </tr>          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../arts-of-asia"><img src="images/arts-of-asia-icon.gif" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Arts of Asia"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>Arts of Asia</b><br>              <a href="http://www.artsmia.org/arts-of-asia">www.artsmia.org/arts-of-asia               </a><br>              Gallery 218<br>              An online project for museum visitors, teachers, and everyone interested               in Asian art, culture, and history.</td>          </tr>          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../face-to-face"><img src="images/face-to-face-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Find Yourself Face to Face"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>Find Yourself Face to Face</b><br>              <a href="../face-to-face">www.artsmia.org/face-to-face</a><br>              Depictions of faces in five works of art from a range of times and               cultures illustrate some of the different reasons people create               art. What can we learn about other people by looking at art? What               can we learn about ourselves?</td>          </tr>		     <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><a href="../get-more"><img src="images/get-more-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Get More from Your Visit"></a></td>            <td width="93%"><b>Get More from Your Visit</b><br>              <a href="../get-more">www.artsmia.org/get-more</a><br>              Get More From Your Visit offers a wealth of resources 			  to help you prepare for your visit to the Institute.</td>          </tr>          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../get-the-picture"><img src="images/get-the-picture-icon.gif" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Get the Picture"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>Get the Picture</b><br>              <a href="../get-the-picture">www.artsmia.org/get-the-picture </a><br>              Get the Picture is an internet-based resource for middle and high               school teachers and students of photography containing more than               50 photographs from the permanent collection of The Minneapolis               Institute of Arts. Get the Picture can be used to teach about both               the process of making pictures and the resulting works of art. </td>          </tr>          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../hartigan"><img src="images/grace-hartigan-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Grace Hartigan's Billboard"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>Grace Hartigan's Billboard</b><br>              <a href="../hartigan">www.artsmia.org/hartigan</a> <br>              Explore an abstract expressionist painter's response in vivid color               to the life of the streets around her. This set of interdisciplinary               lesson ideas takes Grace Hartigan's Billboard as its focus, with               supporting background information and discussion questions.</td>          </tr>		<tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF">             <td width="6%" valign="top"><b><a href="/education/ed-eve-2001/"><img src="images/pastime-pleasure-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Pastime and Pleasure Online"></a></b></td>            <td width="94%" valign="top"><b>Pastime and Pleasure Online</b>               <br>              <a href="/education/ed-eve-2001/">www.artsmia.org/education/ed-eve-2001/</a> <br>			  What do people do for fun? How do artists depict scenes of relaxation, fun with friends, or time alone?  What do artists enjoy about creating art?  Why do people enjoy looking at art?  Explore these questions through a five-part series of lessons based on images from different cultures and times.  The Pastime and Pleasure teacher's guide includes lesson plans and extension ideas adaptable for grades 3-8.</td>          </tr>          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../education/ed-eve-2000/"><img src="images/sense-of-place-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Sense of Place"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>Sense of Place</b><br>              <a href="../education/ed-eve-2000/">www.artsmia.org/education/ed-eve-2000</a><br>              What gives meaning to a place? How does an artist create a sense               of place? What do we learn through our travels in art? Explore these               questions through a five-part series of lessons based on five images               from different times and cultures. A Sense of Place teacher's guide               includes lesson plans and extension ideas adaptable for grades 3-8.</td>          </tr>		            <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../surrounded-by-beauty"><img src="images/sbb-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="Surrounded by Beauty"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>Surrounded by Beauty</b><br>              <a href="../surrounded-by-beauty">www.artsmia.org/surrounded-by-beauty</a><br>              Surrounded by Beauty is an online resource for K - 12 students and teachers 			  featuring Native American works of art from The Minneapolis Institute 			  of Arts' permanent collection.</td>          </tr>          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../ceramics"><img src="images/world-ceramics-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="World Ceramics"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>World Ceramics</b><br>              <a href="../ceramics">www.artsmia.org/ceramics</a><br>              This website examines twelve objects from around the world, created               by a variety of processes. The objects are from ancient to modern               times and come from Mexico, China, United States, Greece, Sweden,               Hungary, Nigeria, England and Japan. World Ceramics teaches about               each object by answering four key questions related to different               aspects of art: where does it come from? (context); what does it               look like? (decoration and style); how was it made? (materials and               techniques); and how was it used? (function).</td>          </tr>          <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">             <td width="7%"><b><a href="../mythology"><img src="images/world-mythology-icon.jpg" width="37" height="45" border="0" hspace="0" alt="World Mythology"></a></b></td>            <td width="93%"><b>World Mythology</b><br>              <a href="../mythology">www.artsmia.org/mythology </a><br>              Myths are imaginative vehicles for making the inexplicable clear.               Images from Europe, Africa, New Ireland, Japan, China and North               America illustrate figures and episodes from the mythologies of               their respective cultures. The accompanying text provides the story               and cultural background of each work of art, encouraging an exploration               of the role mythology plays in a community's identity. Discussion               questions and a framework of categories for comparison are included,               as well as an audiotape of storytellers retelling some of the myths.</td>          </tr>        </table>      </div>      </td>  </TR></TABLE></div><cfinclude template="/site_nav/main_blue.cfm"></BODY></HTML>